        <item>
        <title>Rethinking the Wwise Audio Input Source Plug-in</title>
        <link>https://www.audiokinetic.com/community/blog/rethinking-the-wwise-audio-input-source-plug-in</link>
        <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.audiokinetic.com/community/blog/rethinking-the-wwise-audio-input-source-plug-in</guid>
        <description><![CDATA[<h2>1. Intro</h2>
<p>The <a href="https://www.audiokinetic.com/en/public-library/2025.1.5_9095/?source=SDK&id=referencematerial_audioinput.html" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Audio Input Source Plug-in</a> ships with Wwise and provides a relatively easy way to get audio streams from the game into Wwise, which is used for voice chat, Unreal Audio Link, or, possibly, DSP prototyping. In order to stream audio, it relies on a game-provided global function<sup><a href="#footnotes" rel="noopener">1</a></sup><span> </span>– it’s called from Wwise’s thread every time a relevant voice needs more data, then the game must resolve audio data by the voice’s PlayingID. This global callback, however, while being relatively easy to implement, forces the game to synchronise access to a data structure (or a few) in one place. Not a big deal per se, and things can be made quick and optimised, but the bookkeeping this approach requires sometimes feels like too much.</p>
]]></description>
        <pubDate>Wed, 10 Jun 2026 14:47:00 -0400</pubDate>
    </item>
