        <item>
        <title>Bringing Halloween Displays to Life with Wwise, Unity and Arduino</title>
        <link>https://www.audiokinetic.com/blog/bringing-halloween-displays-to-life-with-wwise-unity-and-arduino</link>
        <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.audiokinetic.com/blog/bringing-halloween-displays-to-life-with-wwise-unity-and-arduino</guid>
        <description><![CDATA[<h2>Introduction</h2>
<p><span>For the past couple years my family has been creating increasingly complicated Halloween displays. What started as a COVID lockdown era project to keep busy has become a yearly opportunity for the family to get together, flex creative muscles, and create something unique for the neighborhood. </span><span style="white-space-collapse: preserve;"><br></span><span style="white-space-collapse: preserve;"><br></span><span style="white-space-collapse: preserve;"><span style="width: 418px; height: 313px;"><img src="https://1940263.fs1.hubspotusercontent-na1.net/hubfs/1940263/undefined-Apr-17-2026-02-50-15-3345-PM.jpeg" width="800" height="600" style="width: 800px; height: auto; max-width: 100%; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; display: block;"></span></span><span style="white-space-collapse: preserve;"><br></span><span style="white-space-collapse: preserve;"><br></span><span>Most years, the focus has been on lights and puppetry with no audio or, at most, some subtle music playing quietly in the background. This felt like such a shame considering I spend every day holed up in front of a DAW creating sound effects. So this past year, I took it upon myself to start incorporating some more intentional audio to the display. While it would’ve been easy to create a light ambience and pipe it around the yard, I thought that this would be a great chance to also add some interactive elements to the display and hopefully take viewers from being observers of the decorations to being a part of the action. </span><span style="white-space-collapse: preserve;"><br><br></span></p>
]]></description>
        <pubDate>Thu, 23 Apr 2026 14:54:51 -0400</pubDate>
    </item>
        <item>
        <title>Behind the Sound of Absolum</title>
        <link>https://www.audiokinetic.com/community/blog/behind-the-sound-of-absolum</link>
        <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.audiokinetic.com/community/blog/behind-the-sound-of-absolum</guid>
        <description><![CDATA[<h2>A Bit of Context<span style="white-space-collapse: preserve;"><br></span><span></span></h2>
<p>After the success of Streets of Rage 4, the development team had the luxury of having the choice for what their next game would be. They could go the easy way, follow up and make a new instalment of the revered franchise (or revive any other one) or be more ambitious and start their own IP, leaving them with a blank canvas.<br><br>Absolutely blank? Not exactly…<br><br>They knew it would be a side scrolling beat ‘em up type of game, and they wanted to expand on some of the great game mechanics featured in SoR4. They also knew they would use Mr. X Nightmare (SoR4 DLC) SURVIVAL mode, its procedural level content generation and Roguelite mechanics, as a basis to create a new and exciting fast-paced thrilling brawler.<br><br>While I had not been part of the development of SoR4 per se, I had been in charge of Mr. X Nightmare’s sound and music implementation (with Tee Lopes in charge of the music composition).<br><br><span>So when starting working on the new project, I was already familiar with the team, the game engine and a good part of the game mechanics, which definitely is a plus when you are the sole person in charge of the audio of a game.</span><span style="white-space-collapse: preserve;"><br></span><span></span></p>
]]></description>
        <pubDate>Thu, 16 Apr 2026 16:39:52 -0400</pubDate>
    </item>
