        <item>
        <title>Dynamic Audio in 2D Run-and-Gun “Neon Inferno”</title>
        <link>https://www.audiokinetic.com/community/blog/dynamic-audio-in-2d-run-and-gun-neon-inferno</link>
        <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.audiokinetic.com/community/blog/dynamic-audio-in-2d-run-and-gun-neon-inferno</guid>
        <description><![CDATA[<h2>Introduction</h2>
<p><span>When we think about dynamic and adaptive audio systems, our minds often jump to sprawling 3D open-world games with massive budgets and teams. It’s easy to understand why, as these productions typically feature large, dynamic environments and complex gameplay systems that generate countless variables for audio to react to. However, this association can create a blind spot: many developers, composers, and sound designers working on indie or 2D projects don’t fully consider the advantages that dynamic audio tools can bring to their games, often limiting themselves to simple audio playback and loops.<br></span></p>]]></description>
        <pubDate>Thu, 26 Feb 2026 16:35:33 -0500</pubDate>
