        <item>
        <title>From Constraint to Creativity: The Music Design of Hell Is Us</title>
        <link>https://www.audiokinetic.com/community/blog/from-constraint-to-creativity-the-music-design-of-hell-is-us</link>
        <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.audiokinetic.com/community/blog/from-constraint-to-creativity-the-music-design-of-hell-is-us</guid>
        <description><![CDATA[<p>When taking over the audio development for Hell Is Us, one thing was at the top of our mind: music design. Our philosophy is that music design is just as important as music composition. Track choices, transitions, silence, and music evolution need not only fit the artistic direction, but also work hand in hand with the game design. A great song that fits the mood but serves no design purpose – or even worse, clashes with the game design – won’t have as much of an emotional impact on the player, and risks creating certain distortions in the final experience. A good game is more than the sum of its parts, a good game comes into being when all departments work in synergy, and music design is key to this.<br><br>For Hell Is Us, we had a singular, unique constraint: non-diegetic elements were not permitted to give clear hints as to whether the player was on the right path or doing the right thing. This is part of the core design philosophy of Hell Is Us — the answers need to come from the player himself. Only the world of Hadea — its citizens, its ruins, the soldiers roaming its war-torn lands — will guide the player where he needs to go.<br><br>This made some situations particularly tricky, as we wanted to create a musical journey that constantly shifts and morphs to accompany the player through each moment. Tricky, but not impossible of course. We are far from being the first team to implement creative multi-layered solutions to elevate music and game design hand-in-hand, but each game is different and requires specific, curated solutions. In the end, when we looked at this challenge, we were delighted to realize that those design constraints ended up turning into creative opportunities. If the music couldn’t give away key hints before the player himself had time to understand and assimilate new elements, then any meaningful melodic and rhythmical changes we wanted to implement had to happen in very subtle ways, and only after the player had absorbed key information. In other words, we had to avoid as much as possible some of the classic music design tricks commonly heard in games: stingers based on locations, pavlovian jingles to reward a behavior, key changes linked to puzzle resolution, etc. That’s not to say we never use any of those throughout the game’s ~30 hour playtime; but Hell Is Us’ unique game design philosophy pushed us into trying new solutions for key moments.<br><br>In this article, I’d like to dive into one of those key moments. As the player inches towards the end of Act 1 of Hell Is Us, he reaches Lake Cynon and dives deep into its mysterious underground ruins, The Lymbic Forge. To score this sequence, we used a multitude of horizontal and vertical transitions, segments and some neat tricks to achieve what we wanted.<br><br>First, let’s look at a simple flowchart explaining the music design for this section of the game:</p>
]]></description>
